# Kotlin best practices

When editing or generating Kotlin in **app/** (Android app), follow the project’s Kotlin best practices:

**`docs/technical/KOTLIN_BEST_PRACTICES.md`**

In short:
- **Naming:** PascalCase classes/files, camelCase functions/properties; one main class per file. Constants UPPER_SNAKE; prefer `core/config` for app config.
- **Null safety:** Prefer non-null types; use `?.`, `?:`, `?.let`; avoid `!!`. Use `List`/`Set`/`Map` (read-only) in APIs.
- **Functions:** Expression bodies when single expression; default parameters; exhaustive `when` on sealed types.
- **Classes:** `data class` for data; `val` over `var`; sealed types for closed hierarchies; composition over inheritance.
- **Coroutines/Flow:** Use `viewModelScope`/application scope; `StateFlow`/`SharedFlow` for hot streams; collect with `repeatOnLifecycle`/`flowWithLifecycle`; `Dispatchers.IO` for IO.
- **Android/Room:** `suspend` DAO for one-shot; `Flow` for reactive queries; ViewModels expose state via StateFlow; Hilt for DI; no hardcoded user-facing strings.
- **Formatting:** 4 spaces, trailing commas, no PII in logs; follow `LOGGING_POLICY.md` and `SECURITY_NOTES.md`.
- **Project rules:** Only End trip writes to trip store; repository chain (domain → data → DAO); util vs utils packages; run Detekt and fix new issues.

Match existing code in the same layer when unclear. Official refs: [Kotlin coding conventions](https://kotlinlang.org/docs/coding-conventions.html), [Android Kotlin style guide](https://developer.android.com/kotlin/style-guide).
